and military strategies—both successful and unsuccessful—that states and international courts have adopted to pursue and capture war crimes suspects. It is a story fraught with broken promises, backroom politics, ethical dilemmas, and daring escapades—all in the name of international justice and human rights.Hiding in Plain Sight is a companion book to the public television documentary Dead Reckoning: Postwar Justice from World War II to The War on Terror. For more information about the documentary, visit www.pbs.org/wnet/dead-reckoning/. And for more information about the Human Rights Center, visit hrc.berkeley.edu.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aInternational criminal courts. 0aWar crime trials. 0aWar crimes investigation. 0aWar crimes. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  a9 11.  abalkan war criminals.  abalkan war.  acrimes against humanity.  acriminal justice.  acriminology.  agenocide.  ahuman rights violations.  ahuman rights.  ainternational courts.  ainternational criminal court.  ainternational justice.  anazi collaborators.  anazi war criminals.  anuremberg.  apolitical crimes.  apost 9 11.  apostwar justice.  aprosecuting terrorists.  arwandan genocide.  asuspected war crimes.  aterrorists.  awar crimes.  awar criminals.  aworld war ii war crimes.  aworlds most wanted.1 aKoenig, Alexa, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aPeskin, Victor, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z97831106675470 cprintz978052029604640uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052096276740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520962767423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/97805209627